"# Chapter 12 — Linear Algebra, Deep

## Opening — The Mathematics of Structure and Transformation

Linear algebra is the mathematics of patterns in straight lines — vectors, matrices, transformations, and the deep structure hiding inside systems of equations. While Book I touched on vectors and basic matrix operations, this chapter goes deeper: we'll factor matrices into their fundamental pieces, find the axes a transformation wants to stretch along, solve overdetermined systems that have no perfect answer, and watch how linear maps reshape space itself.

**A brief history.** The seeds of linear algebra sprouted in the 1600s, when mathematicians solving systems of equations noticed patterns in the coefficients. By the 1800s, matrices had a name (Sylvester, 1850) and determinants had rules (Cauchy, Laplace). The 20th century brought eigenvalues (from the German *eigen*, \"own\" or \"characteristic\") — the idea that a transformation has special directions it only stretches, never rotates. Today, linear algebra is the workhorse of science: it compresses images, finds patterns in data, simulates structures, trains neural networks, solves differential equations, ranks web pages, and powers nearly every algorithm that touches a grid of numbers.

**Uses in the world.** Linear algebra is everywhere computation happens at scale. Google's PageRank is an eigenvector. A recommender system factors a giant preference matrix. A structural engineer solves a stiffness matrix to see where a bridge will bend. A graphics card multiplies transformation matrices sixty times a second. A statistician fits a least-squares line because the exact answer doesn't exist. An image compressor finds the singular values of a pixel matrix and throws away the small ones. A quantum computer stores its state as a vector and evolves it with unitary matrices. Linear algebra is the language machines speak when they see the world as grids of numbers.

**What we'll cover.** We start with the factorizations that break a matrix into interpretable pieces: LU (lower-upper, for efficient solving), QR (orthogonal-triangular, for stable least-squares), and SVD (singular value decomposition, the ultimate factorization). Then eigenvalues and eigenvectors — the \"DNA\" of a matrix, the directions it wants to act along. We'll solve systems that can't be solved exactly (least-squares regression, the best wrong answer). We'll compute rank and nullspace (what's lost, what's preserved). We'll raise matrices to powers and see what happens in the long run. And we'll end by watching a linear transformation act on a cloud of points, reshaping the plane in real time — the geometry behind the arithmetic.

**Utility in Motoi.** the canvas is a dot matrix, and nearly everything she builds rests on linear algebra. When she rotates a shape, she multiplies by a rotation matrix. When she projects a 3D curve onto the screen, she applies a projection matrix. When she fits a curve to noisy data, she solves a least-squares problem. When she wants to know if a set of constraints has a solution, she checks the rank. When she simulates a network (Markov chains, PageRank), she finds the dominant eigenvector. When she compresses a signal or image, she uses SVD. Deep linear algebra is the foundation under the floor — the reason the shapes move the way they do.

**The ramp.** We'll start gently — a 2×2 matrix, a small system, a visible determinant — and climb topic by topic into the genuine deep end: eigenvalues of larger matrices, least-squares fitting real data, transformations acting on the plane. Every topic opens with something almost anyone can run, then ramps within. By the summit, we'll decompose a matrix into eigenvalues and eigenvectors and paint the transformation it describes.

---

## Topic 1 — Matrices and Vectors, Refreshed

Before we factor and decompose, let's make sure the basic objects — vectors, matrices, and their arithmetic — are clear. A **vector** is an ordered list of numbers (we build them with `vec/make`). A **matrix** is a rectangular grid of numbers (we build them with `matrix/make`, passing a list of rows). We can add, subtract, scale, multiply, and transpose them.

**Simple vector arithmetic.**

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3 4))
(define w (vec/make 1 2))

(define sum (vec/+ v w))
(define diff (vec/- v w))
(define scaled (vec/scale v 2))

(list 'v v 'w w 'sum sum 'diff diff 'scaled scaled)
```
[VISUAL: text output listing the vectors and results]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify vec/ verbs; print result -->

**Matrix construction and basic operations.**

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                              (list 3 4))))
(define B (matrix/make (list (list 5 6)
                              (list 7 8))))

(define sum (matrix/+ A B))
(define diff (matrix/- A B))
(define product (matrix/* A B))

(list 'A A 'B B 'sum sum 'product product)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the 2×2 matrices and results]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify matrix/ verbs; print result -->

**Transpose flips rows and columns.**

```scheme
(define M (matrix/make (list (list 1 2 3)
                              (list 4 5 6))))

(define Mt (matrix/transpose M))

(list 'M M 'transpose Mt)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing M (2×3) and Mt (3×2)]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**The identity matrix** is the \"do nothing\" transformation — multiplying by it leaves a matrix unchanged.

```scheme
(define I3 (matrix/identity 3))

(define A (matrix/make (list (list 2 1 0)
                              (list 0 3 1)
                              (list 1 0 2))))

(define product (matrix/* A I3))

(list 'A A 'I3 I3 'A*I3 product)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the identity and that A * I = A]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Matrix-vector multiplication** transforms a vector.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 2 0)
                              (list 0 3))))
(define v (vec/make 1 1))

(define result (matrix/* A (matrix/make (list (list 1) (list 1)))))

(list 'A A 'v v 'Av result)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the matrix A and the transformed vector (a 2×1 matrix result)]
<!-- BUILD: run; show that the 2×2 matrix scales the vector's components differently -->

**Determinant** measures \"signed volume scaling\" — if zero, the matrix squashes space flat (not invertible).

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 3 1)
                              (list 2 4))))

(define det (matrix/determinant A))

(list 'A A 'determinant det)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing det(A) = 10]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**A singular (non-invertible) matrix has determinant zero.**

```scheme
(define S (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                              (list 2 4))))

(define det (matrix/determinant S))

(list 'S S 'determinant det)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing det = 0]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**The inverse** of a matrix undoes it: A * A⁻¹ = I.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 4 3)
                              (list 3 2))))

(define Ainv (linalg/inverse A))

(define product (matrix/* A Ainv))

(list 'A A 'A-inv Ainv 'A*A-inv product)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing A, its inverse, and A * A⁻¹ ≈ I]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result; check for numerical near-identity -->

**A singular matrix has no inverse** — the verb returns an escalation.

```scheme
(define S (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                              (list 2 4))))

(define attempt (linalg/inverse S))

(list 'S S 'inverse-attempt attempt)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing an (escalate ...) result]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify honest-null contract (escalate on singular) -->

**Transpose of a product reverses the order:** (AB)ᵀ = BᵀAᵀ.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                              (list 3 4))))
(define B (matrix/make (list (list 5 6)
                              (list 7 8))))

(define AB (matrix/* A B))
(define AB-transpose (matrix/transpose AB))

(define Bt (matrix/transpose B))
(define At (matrix/transpose A))
(define BtAt (matrix/* Bt At))

(list 'AB-transpose AB-transpose 'BtAt BtAt 'equal? (matrix/= AB-transpose BtAt))
```
[VISUAL: text output verifying the identity]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Matrix powers** — multiplying a matrix by itself repeatedly.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 1)
                              (list 0 1))))

(define A2 (linalg/matrix-power A 2))
(define A3 (linalg/matrix-power A 3))

(list 'A A 'A^2 A2 'A^3 A3)
```
