## Topic 3 — LU Factorization

**LU decomposition** factors a matrix A into a product **A = LU**, where L is **lower triangular** (nonzero only on and below the diagonal) and U is **upper triangular** (nonzero only on and above the diagonal). This is Gaussian elimination, stored as matrices. It's useful because once you have L and U, solving Ax = b becomes two easy triangular solves: first Ly = b (forward substitution), then Ux = y (backward substitution).

**LU factorization of a 2×2 matrix.**

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 4 3)
                              (list 6 3))))

(define factorization (linalg/lu A))

(list 'A A 'LU factorization)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the original matrix and the LU factorization (typically a tagged structure with L and U)]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify linalg/lu; print result -->

**LU of a 3×3 matrix.**

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 2 1 1)
                              (list 4 3 3)
                              (list 8 7 9))))

(define factorization (linalg/lu A))

factorization
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the LU factorization]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**LU fails on a singular matrix** — escalates.

```scheme
(define S (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                              (list 2 4))))

(define attempt (linalg/lu S))

(list 'S S 'LU-attempt attempt)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing an (escalate ...) result]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify escalation -->

**LU of a 4×4 matrix.**

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 0 0 0)
                              (list 2 1 0 0)
                              (list 3 2 1 0)
                              (list 4 3 2 1))))

(define factorization (linalg/lu A))

factorization
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the LU factorization of a lower-triangular-like structure]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

