## Topic 7 — Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors

An **eigenvector** of a matrix A is a nonzero vector v such that **Av = λv** for some scalar λ (the **eigenvalue**). Geometrically, A stretches v by a factor of λ but doesn't change its direction. Eigenvalues and eigenvectors reveal the \"DNA\" of a linear transformation — the directions it acts along and how much it stretches or shrinks them. They're central to stability analysis, Markov chains, quantum mechanics, principal component analysis, Google's PageRank, and much more.

**Eigenvalues of a 2×2 matrix** — the wired verb computes them.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 4 1)
                              (list 2 3))))

(define evals (linalg/eigenvalues A))

(list 'A A 'eigenvalues evals)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the two eigenvalues (could be real or complex)]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify linalg/eigenvalues; print result -->

**Eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix** are just the diagonal entries.

```scheme
(define D (matrix/make (list (list 5 0)
                              (list 0 3))))

(define evals (linalg/eigenvalues D))

(list 'D D 'eigenvalues evals)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing [5, 3]]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix** are always real.

```scheme
(define S (matrix/make (list (list 2 1)
                              (list 1 2))))

(define evals (linalg/eigenvalues S))

(list 'S S 'eigenvalues evals)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing two real eigenvalues]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Specialized 2×2 eigenvalue solver** (direct formula).

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 3 1)
                              (list 1 3))))

(define evals (linalg/eigenvalues-2x2 A))

(list 'A A 'eigenvalues-2x2 evals)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing [4, 2]]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify linalg/eigenvalues-2x2; print result -->

