## Topic 10 — Orthogonality and Projections

Two vectors are **orthogonal** if their dot product is zero — they're perpendicular. A set of vectors is **orthonormal** if each has length 1 and they're mutually orthogonal. **Projection** of a vector onto another is the \"shadow\" it casts — the component along that direction. Projection onto a subspace (like the column space of a matrix) is the foundation of least-squares.

**Dot product and orthogonality.**

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 0))
(define v (vec/make 0 1))

(define dot (vec/dot u v))

(list 'u u 'v v 'dot-product dot 'orthogonal? (= dot 0))
```
[VISUAL: text output showing dot = 0, orthogonal = #t]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify vec/dot; print result -->

**Dot product of non-orthogonal vectors.**

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 2))
(define v (vec/make 3 4))

(define dot (vec/dot u v))

(list 'u u 'v v 'dot-product dot)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing dot = 11]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Check if a matrix is orthogonal** (QᵀQ = I).

```scheme
(define Q (matrix/make (list (list (/ 1 (math/sqrt 2)) (/ 1 (math/sqrt 2)))
                              (list (/ -1 (math/sqrt 2)) (/ 1 (math/sqrt 2))))))

(define orth? (linalg/is-orthogonal? Q))

(list 'Q Q 'orthogonal? orth?)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing #t]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify linalg/is-orthogonal?; print result -->

**Projection of a vector onto another.**

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3 4))
(define u (vec/make 1 0))

(define proj (linalg/project v u))

(list 'v v 'u u 'projection-of-v-onto-u proj)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the projection]
<!-- BUILD: run; verify linalg/project; print result -->

**Projection onto a line in 2D.**

```scheme
