## Topic 13 — Markov Chains and the Dominant Eigenvector

A **Markov chain** is a system that transitions between states with fixed probabilities. The **transition matrix** P has columns that are probability vectors (sum to 1, nonnegative). The long-term behavior is governed by the **dominant eigenvector** (eigenvalue 1) — the **stationary distribution**. This is the math behind Google's PageRank, recommendation algorithms, and many random processes.

**A simple 2-state Markov chain.**

```scheme
;; States: A, B
;; Transition: A->A 0.7, A->B 0.3, B->A 0.4, B->B 0.6
(define P (matrix/make (list (list 0.7 0.4)
                              (list 0.3 0.6))))

(define state0 (matrix/make (list (list 1) (list 0))))  ; start in state A

(define state1 (matrix/* P state0))
(define state2 (matrix/* P state1))

(list 'P P 'state0 state0 'state1 state1 'state2 state2)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the state distribution after 1 and 2 steps]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Long-term behavior** — raise P to a high power (or find the stationary distribution).

```scheme
(define P (matrix/make (list (list 0.7 0.4)
                              (list 0.3 0.6))))

(define P10 (linalg/matrix-power P 10))
(define P20 (linalg/matrix-power P 20))

(list 'P P 'P^10 P10 'P^20 P20)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the transition matrix converging to a steady state]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**Stationary distribution from the dominant eigenvector** (eigenvalue 1).

```scheme
(define P (matrix/make (list (list 0.8 0.3)
                              (list 0.2 0.7))))

(define evals (linalg/eigenvalues P))
(define evecs (linalg/eigenvectors P))

(list 'P P 'eigenvalues evals 'eigenvectors evecs)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing eigenvalue 1 and the corresponding stationary distribution vector]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

**A 3-state Markov chain.**

```scheme
(define P (matrix/make (list (list 0.5 0.2 0.3)
                              (list 0.3 0.6 0.1)
                              (list 0.2 0.2 0.6))))

(define state0 (matrix/make (list (list 1) (list 0) (list 0))))

(define state5 (linalg/matrix-power P 5))
(define final (matrix/* state5 state0))

(list 'P P 'state-after-5-steps final)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the state distribution after 5 transitions]
<!-- BUILD: run; print result -->

