## Topic 15 — Matrix Norms and Conditioning

A **matrix norm** measures the \"size\" of a matrix. The **condition number** of a matrix A (ratio of largest to smallest singular value) measures how sensitive the solution of Ax = b is to small changes in b or A. A high condition number means the system is **ill-conditioned** — small errors can blow up.

**Frobenius norm of a matrix** (conceptual, sum of squares of entries).

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 3 4)
                              (list 0 0))))

;; Frobenius norm = sqrt(3^2 + 4^2) = 5
;; (No direct verb, but we can compute manually)

(define entries (list 3 4 0 0))
(define sum-sq (fold + 0 (map (lambda (x) (* x x)) entries)))
(define frob-norm (math/sqrt sum-sq))

(list 'A A 'Frobenius-norm frob-norm)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing the Frobenius norm]
<!-- BUILD: run; manual computation of Frobenius norm -->

**Condition number (conceptual, via SVD).**

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 10 7)
                              (list 7 5))))

(define svd-result (linalg/svd A))

;; Condition number = max singular value / min singular value
;; (Extract from svd-result if structure allows; otherwise, conceptual note)

(list 'A A 'SVD svd-result 'condition-number-concept \"ratio of singular values\")
```
[VISUAL: text output showing SVD and a note on condition number]
<!-- BUILD: run; conceptual demonstration -->

---

## Topic 16 — Advanced: Jordan Normal Form, Generalized Eigenvectors (Conceptual)

Not all matrices are diagonalizable. When a matrix has **defective eigenvalues** (geometric multiplicity < algebraic multiplicity), it can't be fully diagonalized, but it can be put into **Jordan normal form** — a block-diagonal matrix with 1s on the super-diagonal. This requires **generalized eigenvectors**. It's advanced territory, often covered in a second linear algebra course.

**Conceptual note on Jordan form.**

```scheme
(list 'Jordan-form-concept
      \"Some matrices cannot be diagonalized (e.g. [[1 1][0 1]]). They have a Jordan block structure. This requires generalized eigenvectors and is beyond the current wired surface.\")
```
[VISUAL: text output with a conceptual note]
<!-- BUILD: conceptual note; no direct Jordan verb wired -->

